Joe,<br><br>
What a tough question!<br><br>
Looking at the Vietnam War is like looking through a kaliedoscope of mistakes, tainted motives, and victimization, with multitudes of lessons.<br><br>
In my view, the single most influential lesson is:<br><br>
If you are going to fight, do it to win!<br><br>
-or-<br><br>
Do not fight if your intentions are less than honorable!<br><br>
Many of the political, military, and emotional problems with the Vietnam War would have been averted if this country had a clear objective and mandate. We clearly had neither.<br><br>
The politicians were a joke. Between Johnson's pork barrel mentality and leadership incompetance, and McNamara's academic goof ball view of reality, no one stood a chance.<br><br>
The military was a joke. Between rotations of decoration hungry officers and the bizarre conduct of battle, combined with more goof ball views of reality, no one stood a chance. <br><br>
The country was a joke. Emotionally, the country was divided and because no one had the presence of mind to give due consideration to those who fought in the Vietnam War, no one stood a chance. <br><br>
I make no apology for this point of view. It is my reality.<br>
A personal &quot;lesson&quot; is that I will be the first in line with a protest sign if I ever see anything like the Vietnam War again.<br><br>

